Agree, nice!

I sent the below to the other chain:

1) This is taking Sanders' costs (the $13.7 trillion) at face value, and
saying he falls short. On top of that, the Thorpe piece from last week says
that Sanders' plan underestimates costs by ~$11 trillion over 10 years (and
that's why he needs 20% tax to pay for it), so if this were right, that
picture would look worse
2) TPC - a more solid source - has hinted that Sanders would fall short
(here by at least $1.3 trillion) -
http://taxvox.taxpolicycenter.org/2016/01/19/bernie-sanders-is-proposing-re=
ally-big-tax-increases/
3) We should be careful citing to CRFB - they're credible, but are very
very focused on the debt/deficits in a way that we/progressives probably
don't want to overly associate ourselves with - and they will inevitably
say we're not focused enough on long-term debt


